ted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTransience is found in every meeting and form of coexistence between people and things that live and exist by, or move across or along, the Black Sea. It may come in various forms and guises, from de facto states, tourism, migration, trafficking or military troops, and it needs to be written and captured in sensuous, affective and imaginative ways. With particular attention to poetics, politics and aesthetics, this volume focuses on the scales of transient moments and histories, and enables readers to see and sense the many forms of transience that occur in a given landscape, sea or space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEthnologyzBlack Sea Region. 0aHuman geographyzBlack Sea Region. 0aMaterial culturezBlack Sea Region. 0aSocial interactionzBlack Sea Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology (General), Sociology, Environmental Studies (General).1 aDziapshipa, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrederiksen, Martin Demant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrederiksen, Martin Demant, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGavashelishvili, Elene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphrey, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKHALVASHI, TAMTA, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKhalvashi, Tamta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorsby, Trine Mygind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaisuradze, Giorgi, econtributor.4c